intro: |-
  These core typographic styles are used throughout `ChromeOS.dev` and serve as the building blocks for other typography throughout the site.

headlines: |-
  Headlines on `ChromeOS.dev` do not use global fixed breakpoints. Instead, they leverage a flexible approach to headlines based on the current viewport width, utilizing the CSS [`clamp`](https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/CSS/clamp) function.

  In browsers that don't support `clamp`, a medium size between the smallest and largest sizes the headline can grow is used.

  All headlines are typeset in Google Sans. Sizes are given in `px` but converted to `em` (for `font-size`) or a ratio (for `line-height`) when implemented. Headlines are all `--grey-900` (`#202124`).

  In long-form text, headers use one heading size smaller than described here, so an `h1` will be styled as an `h2`, an `h2` will be styled as an `h3`, etc…

fixed: |-
  These type styles do not change based on screen size or where they are displayed. When rendered, `font-size`, `letter-spacing`, `padding` are converted to `em` and `line-height` is converted to a ratio.
