    <p class="type--base">Base copy</p>
    <p class="type type--base">This is regular-sized body copy, used for most body copy. The following is filler to help flesh out what this looks like for long stretches of text. There's also some <strong>bold</strong> and <em>italic</em> text thrown in for god measure. There's so many poorly chosen words in that sentence. I hear the jury's still out on science. That's why you always leave a note! I don't understand the question, and I won't respond to it. I care deeply for nature. I'm half machine. I'm a monster.</p>
    <div class="type">
      <p>Regular body styling can be applied with the <code>.type--base</code> class. It's set in Google sans with a weight of <code>400</code>, colored using <code>--grey-900</code>, and is typeset at <code>16px</code>/<code>24px</code>.</p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="style-guide__section">
    <p class="type--large">Large copy</p>
    <p class="type type--large">This is large-sized body copy, used for shorter blocks of marketing copy, generally found on landing pages. The following is filler to help flesh out what this looks like for long stretches of text. There's also some <strong>bold</strong> and <em>italic</em> text thrown in for god measure. There's so many poorly chosen words in that sentence. I hear the jury's still out on science. That's why you always leave a note! I don't understand the question, and I won't respond to it. I care deeply for nature. I'm half machine. I'm a monster.</p>
    <div class="type">
      <p>Large body styling can be applied with the <code>.type--large</code> class. It's set in Google sans with a weight of <code>400</code>, colored using <code>--grey-900</code>, and is typeset at <code>18px</code>/<code>27px</code>.</p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="style-guide__section">
    <small class="type--eyebrow">Eyebrow</small>
    <div class="type">
      <p>
        Eyebrows are used to give context to content, should be used with the <a href="https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/HTML/Element/small"><code>&lt;small&gt;</code></a> element, and its styling can be applied with the <code>.type--eyebrow</code> class. It's set in Google Sans with a weight of <code>700</code>, colored using <code>--grey-900</code>, set in all caps, has a letter spacing of <code>0.01em</code>, and is typeset at <code>14px</code>/<code>14px</code>.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="style-guide__section">
    <small class="type--small">Small text</small>
    <div class="type">
      <p>
        Small text is used for supplemental information usually towards the end of pages (e.g. sources, disclaimers, and tags), should be used with the <a href="https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/HTML/Element/small"><code>&lt;small&gt;</code></a> element, and its styling can be applied with the <code>.type--small</code> class. It's set in Google Sans Text with a weight of <code>400</code>, colored using <code>--grey-700</code>, and is typeset at <code>12px</code>/<code>16px</code>.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="style-guide__section">
    <p class="type--label">Label text</p>
    <div class="type">
      <p>Label text is as a descriptor for smaller interaction elements (e.g. article tags, TOC title, etc…) and its styling can be applied with the <code>.type--label</code> class. It's set in Google Sans Text with a weight of <code>600</code>, colored using <code>--grey-900</code>, set in all caps, and is typeset at <code>11px</code>/<code>16px</code>.</p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="style-guide__section">
    <figcaption class="type--caption">Caption text.</figcaption>
    <div class="type">
      <p>Caption text is used for image captions and its styling can be applied with the <code>.type--caption</code> class. It's set in Google Sans Text with a weight of <code>400</code>, colored using <code>--grey-900</code>, and is typeset at <code>12px</code>/<code>16.8px</code>.</p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="style-guide__section">
    <p>This is <code class="type--code">Inline Code</code> inside some longer text.</p>
    <div class="type">
      <p>Inline code is used to display monospaced text, usually code, in-line with other text or where other in-line text can go, and its styling can be applied with the <code>.type--code</code> class. It's set in Google Sans Text Mono with a weight of <code>400</code>, colored using <code>--grey-700</code>, has a background of <code>--grey-100</code>, padding of <code>4px</code>, and is typeset at <code>14px</code>/<code>20px</code>.</p>
